body:
## Proposed changes

Issue Number: close #xxx

Since #24830 introduce `broker.name` in hms catalog, data scan will run on specified brokers.
And [doris operator](https://github.com/selectdb/doris-operator) support BE and broker deployed in same pod, BE access local broker is the fastest approach to access data.
In previous logic, every inputSplit will select one BE to execute,  then randomly select one broker for actual data access, BE and related broker are always located on  separate K8S pod.
This pr optimizes the broker select strategy to prioritize BE-local broker when `broker.name` is specified in hms catalog.

title: [Feature](group commit) move group_commit_interval_ms from be.conf to table property
body:
## Proposed changes

Issue Number: close #xxx

<!--Describe your changes.-->

Current batch commit interval is configured in be.conf with the property "group_commit_interval_ms". It has the following drawbacks:

1. The interval is the same for all tables, and cannot be configured differently.
2. If the configuration is modified, all BEs need to be modified and restarted.

Considering that the commit interval is a table-level configuration, it is possible to move this configuration from be.conf to table properties. If not explicitly set, the default value is 10000ms. Users can modify it as follows:

```SQL
ALTER TABLE my_table SET ("group_commit_interval_ms"="1000");
```

Each time BE requests a plan from FE, it can be passed over.

## Further comments

If this is a relatively large or complex change, kick off the discussion at [dev@doris.apache.org](mailto:dev@doris.apache.org) by explaining why you chose the solution you did and what alternatives you considered, etc...

title: [fix](nereids)count in correlated subquery shoud not output null value
body:
consider sql: SELECT * FROM t1 WHERE t1.a <= (SELECT COUNT(t2.a) FROM t2 WHERE (t1.b = t2.b)); 
when unnest correlated subquery, we create a left join node. Assume outer query is left table and subquery is right one.
If there is no match, the row from right table is filled with nulls.
But COUNT function is always not nullable. So wrap COUNT with Nvl to ensure it's result is 0 instead of null to get the correct result
